All four tests pass. The existing test suite is already a tight, contract-focused property-based suite. Here is the summary of what each test captures and what was deliberately left out.

## Tests and contract clauses

**`known_values`** ‚Äî concrete sanity anchors. Catches an implementation that wires `q` and `r` in the wrong order, or that special-cases `a == 0` / `b == 1` incorrectly. Not a contract clause on its own, but a cheap guard against gross wiring errors.

**`quotient_remainder_identity`** ‚Äî *postcondition* (Euclidean identity). Exhaustively checks `q * b + r == a` and `r < b` for `a ‚àà [0, 50]`, `b ‚àà [1, 50]`. Together these two conditions *uniquely* characterize `(q, r)` for unsigned division, so any implementation that satisfies them on these inputs is functionally correct on these inputs.

**`boundary_identity`** ‚Äî *postcondition* at the type boundary. Same Euclidean check at `u64::MAX`, `u64::MAX - 1`, etc. Catches an implementation that uses a narrower intermediate type (e.g. `u32` truncation) or mishandles the top of the range. The check `q*b + r == a` cannot itself overflow because `a ‚â§ u64::MAX`.

**`panics_on_zero_divisor`** ‚Äî *failure condition*. Pins down that `b == 0` panics rather than returning a sentinel or wrapping silently.

## Properties deliberately not tested (and why)

- **`a % b == a` when `a < b`**, **`a / b == 0` when `a < b`**, **`a / a == 1`**, **`a / 1 == a`**, **`(a*b) / b == a`**, etc. ‚Äî All are *derived* from the Euclidean identity `q*b + r = a, r < b`, which already uniquely determines `(q,r)`. Adding them inflates the proof obligation count without constraining the implementation further.
- **Monotonicity in `a`** (`a1 ‚â§ a2 ‚üπ a1/b ‚â§ a2/b`) ‚Äî derived from the identity.
- **Consistency between the two outputs** (`div_rem(a,b).0 == a/b` and `.1 == a%b`) ‚Äî this is essentially the *definition* used in the implementation; testing it would not distinguish a buggy from a correct version, only restate the source.
- **Idempotence of `%`** (`(a%b) % b == a%b`) ‚Äî follows from `r < b`.
- **Distributivity / additive properties** (`(a+b)/b == a/b + 1` for `b > 0`) ‚Äî derived facts, would only catch bugs already caught by the Euclidean identity.

The suite is intentionally minimal: one defining postcondition, one boundary check of the same postcondition, one failure-condition test, and a handful of concrete anchors.

